2. Definitions

    "Licensed Work" means the software and source code contained in this repository, including any
    files, build scripts, configuration, and documentation distributed with it.

    "Licensor" means the copyright holder(s) of the Licensed Work, including the person or entity
    identified by the copyright notice above.

    "Upstream Repository" means the original public repository designated by the Licensor for the
    Licensed Work:
    https://github.com/funwilliam/Inventory-QR

    If the Upstream Repository URL changes, the Licensor may designate a new Upstream Repository in a
    prominent notice in the repository (e.g., README). Such designation applies prospectively.

    "You" means any individual or legal entity exercising permissions granted by this license.

    "Production Use" means any use by or for the benefit of a company, organization, or other legal
    entity (including internal use) in connection with its actual business operations, including use to
    record, track, manage, audit, or make decisions about real assets, inventory, equipment, materials,
    customers, orders, or internal operational processes, regardless of whether the software is
    accessed via a network/intranet/Internet or used fully offline/on-device.

    "Non-Production Use" means evaluation, learning, personal use, or demonstrations that do not
    constitute Production Use.

    For avoidance of doubt, Non-Production Use includes time-limited internal evaluation or testing
    that (i) does not record or operate on real business assets/workflows and (ii) does not produce
    outputs used for operational business decisions.

    "Fork" means any copy, modification, or derivative work of the Licensed Work.

    "Deployment" includes integrating the Licensed Work or a Fork with any organization system or
    workflow (including databases, identity systems, internal APIs, proprietary UIs, or deployment
    pipelines), and/or modifying it for such integration.

    "Corresponding Source" means the preferred form of the work for making modifications, including
    all source code, build scripts/configuration, packaging/deployment configuration, and dependency
    manifests necessary to produce the deployed artifact by an authorized user with lawful access to
    any excluded third-party materials.

    "Your Modifications" means any modifications, enhancements, patches, bug fixes, or derivative works
    you create that are based on or incorporate the Licensed Work.

    "First Production Use Date" means the first calendar date on which You (or anyone acting on Your
    behalf) begins Production Use. For avoidance of doubt, it is the earliest date on which the
    Licensed Work or a Fork is first used to record, track, or operate on real business assets or real
    operational workflows, or the earliest date on which its outputs are first used for operational
    business decisions.

    "Ceased Production Use" means You have stopped all Production Use of the Licensed Work, any Fork,
    and any Deployment across your organization. If You later resume Production Use at any time, You
    must again satisfy option (A) or option (B) at that time.

    "Public Repository" means a git repository that is publicly accessible for viewing and cloning
    without requiring individualized access approval (e.g., not restricted to a closed group or by
    case-by-case whitelisting), and that contains the complete Corresponding Source required by this
    license.

3. Non-Production Grant (free)

    Subject to the terms of this license, You may copy, modify, and redistribute the Licensed Work for
    Non-Production Use.

    Production Use: Choose ONE path

4. For Production Use, You must satisfy ONE of the following:

    (A) Paid Commercial License
    You have obtained a paid commercial license from the Licensor under separate written terms.

    OR

    (B) Publish-to-Git (no charge)
    Within 14 days of the First Production Use Date, You must:

    1) Publish the complete Corresponding Source of Your Fork (including all modifications to the
        Licensed Work) in a Public Repository (e.g., GitHub, GitLab, or any publicly accessible git
        hosting); and

    2) License that Public Repository under GNU GPL v3.0 (GPL-3.0-only); and

        If You are unable or unwilling to license Your Fork under GPL-3.0-only, You must choose
        option (A) instead.

    3) Keep the Public Repository publicly accessible for as long as You continue Production Use.

        After You have Ceased Production Use, You may make the repository private or remove it.
        If You later resume Production Use, You must again satisfy option (A) or option (B) at that
        time.

        If You resume Production Use after having Ceased Production Use, the deadlines in option (B)
        (including the 14-day publication requirement and the notice requirement) apply again from
        the date You resume Production Use.

    4) Retain this LICENSE file and all copyright notices; and

    5) Include clear, reproducible build/packaging instructions sufficient to produce the deployed
        artifact from source (a README is acceptable); and

    6) Provide NOTICE to the Licensor:
        - Within 3 business days after publishing the Public Repository (or as soon as reasonably
        practicable if a hosting platform outage or similar circumstance prevents timely posting),
        You must notify the Licensor by opening an issue on the Upstream Repository with the title:
            "Production-or-Publish License Compliance Notice: <Organization Name>"
        The issue body must include:
            a) the URL of the Public Repository;
            b) the First Production Use Date;
            c) the Organization name (legal entity) and a contact GitHub account.

        If opening an issue is not possible (e.g., issues disabled), You must instead provide the
        same notice via a contact method designated by the Licensor in the Upstream Repository
        (e.g., email address in README). If no contact method is designated, You must publish the
        notice in the Public Repository README under a section titled
        "Production-or-Publish License Compliance Notice" with the same required fields.

        Notice is deemed given on the date it is publicly posted (issue or README) or emailed to
        the designated contact method, whichever is applicable.

    Third-party dependencies note (option B):
    If Your Fork depends on third-party materials that You are not legally permitted to publish
    (e.g., proprietary SDKs, paid assets), 
    You must:
        i) exclude only those materials from the Public Repository; and
        ii) clearly document how an authorized user can obtain them; and
        iii) ensure the remaining published source is sufficient to reproduce the deployed artifact by
        an authorized user.

    This exception may not be used to withhold Your Modifications to the Licensed Work.

    Contribution License-Back (required for option B):
    By choosing option (B), You grant the Licensor a perpetual, worldwide, irrevocable,
    non-exclusive, royalty-free license to use, reproduce, modify, create derivative works of,
    and distribute Your Modifications, and to sublicense Your Modifications under any terms,
    including proprietary/commercial terms.

    This grant applies only to the extent You have rights in Your Modifications and does not
    override third-party rights.

    By choosing option (B), You represent that You have the right to grant the above license for
    Your Modifications.

    If You do not meet (A) or (B), You do not have permission for Production Use.

